    "title": "MCP separates tool availability from tool invocation",
    "status": "budding",
    "planted": "2026-05-10",
    "tended": "2026-05-10",
    "lede": "The MCP server owns what tools exist and how to call them.",
    "body": "<p>The MCP server owns what tools exist and how to call them. The MCP client owns how those tools get presented to the model and how results are returned.</p>\n<p>The model only sees tool names and schemas, it never talks to the server directly.</p>\n<p>This separation means you can change which model you're using without touching the server, and you can add tools to the server without touching the client or the model.</p>\n<p>See: <a data-note=\"mcp-server-catalogs-available-tools-that-agents-can-query\" href=\"?stack=mcp-server-catalogs-available-tools-that-agents-can-query\">MCP Server catalogs available tools that agents can query</a>, <a data-note=\"mcp-enables-model-integrations-through-a-standard-interface\" href=\"?stack=mcp-enables-model-integrations-through-a-standard-interface\">MCP enables model integrations through a standard interface</a></p>"
